  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "The SOFA score is a scoring system to determine the extent of a person's organ function or rate of failure.\n[1]\n[2]\n[3]\nThe score is based on six different scores based on the organ system involved.\nUse the worst value in a 24-hour period.",
      "subsections": {
        "Predicting_Outcomes": {
          "text": "Both the mean and highest SOFA scores being predictors of outcome.\nAn increase in SOFA score during the first 24 - 48 hours in the ICU predicts a mortality rate of at least 50% up to 95%. Scores less than 9 give predictive mortality at 33% while above 11 can be close to or above 95%\n[4]\nA SOFA score ≥2 reflects an overall mortality risk of approximately 10% in a general hospital population with suspected infection\n[5]\nSOFA (AUROC = 0.74; 95% CI, 0.73-0.76) was superior to that with SIRS (AUROC = 0.64; 95% CI, 0.62-0.66) when used in the ICU\nSOFA (AUROC = 0.79; 95% CI, 0.78-0.80) or change in SOFA score (AUROC = 0.79; 95% CI, 0.78-0.79) was similar to that with SIRS (AUROC = 0.76; 95% CI, 0.75-0.77) when used outside of the ICU",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
